                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410405-name-1306" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1306" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1306" type="surname" value="MARRINER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1306" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN MARRINER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and keep a shop. About six o'clock in the evening, of the 30th of March, the prisoner came into my shop and offered me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for something—I went for change—I then went to the door to another customer—I saw the prisoner moving from the front of the counter to the side, and then he moved back—I saw the end of the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184104050187"></xptr>
               <p>violin under his cloak—he then walked out of the shop, and waited on the step till the child came back with the change—he hand out his hand for the 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change, which I was to give him for the waste-paper—I was going to give him the halfpence and said, "Stop, let me see what you have under your cloak," pulling his cloak on one side—he said, "Don't make a fuss about it, what it the value of it?" or words to that effect—I said it was a great shame for a person of his appearance to come and wrong me—this is my violin.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I have been paralyzed two years, and have not been right in my head, and have been subject to do such things as that.</p>
